All the passages I have cited from Catullus come in the episode of Theseus and Ariadne, beautiful in itself but singularly interrupting the theme of the poem 3 while the passages from Lucretius are scattered through his poem. One might surmise that this episode was filled up by the poet, when he was fresh from reading the new work of Lucretius—I am by no means inclined to retract the above in consequence of the long polemio with which I have been honoured by Mr Julius J essen in a recent pamphlet on this subject, p. 5—15: he will see, if he attends to my general argument, that I no- where imply, or mean to imply, that Catullus has no reminiscences of Lucr. in other parts of his 64th poem: my words assert the very con- r trary 3 I only maintain that they are peculiarly frequent in the episode
